# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uvloop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:uvloop/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:uvloop/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:uvloop/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:uvloop/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:uvloop/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In computer science, an algorithm is called **non-blocking** if failure or suspension of any thread cannot cause failure or suspension of another thread; for some operations, these algorithms provide a useful alternative to traditional blocking implementations.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] A non-blocking algorithm is **lock-free** if there is guaranteed system-wide progress, and **wait-free** if there is also guaranteed per-thread progress.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] "Non-blocking" was used as a synonym for "lock-free" in the literature until the introduction of obstruction-freedom in 2003.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] The word "non-blocking" was traditionally used to describe telecommunications networks that could route a connection through a set of relays "without having to re-arrange existing calls" (see Clos network).
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Also, if the telephone exchange "is not defective, it can always make the connection" (see nonblocking minimal spanning switch).
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] The traditional approach to multi-threaded programming is to use locks to synchronize access to shared resources.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes, semaphores, and critical sections are all mechanisms by which a programmer can ensure that certain sections of code do not execute concurrently, if doing so could corrupt shared memory structures.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] If one thread attempts to acquire a lock that is already held by another thread, the thread will block until the lock is free.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Blocking a thread can be undesirable for many reasons.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] An obvious reason is that while the thread is blocked, it cannot accomplish anything: if the blocked thread had been performing a high-priority or real-time task, it would be highly undesirable to halt its progress.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, certain interactions between locks can lead to error conditions such as deadlock, livelock, and priority inversion.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Using locks also involves a trade-off between coarse-grained locking, which can significantly reduce opportunities for parallelism, and fine-grained locking, which requires more careful design, increases locking overhead and is more prone to bugs.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Unlike blocking algorithms, non-blocking algorithms do not suffer from these downsides, and in addition are safe for use in interrupt handlers: even though the preempted thread cannot be resumed, progress is still possible without it.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In contrast, global data structures protected by mutual exclusion cannot safely be accessed in an interrupt handler, as the preempted thread may be the one holding the lock.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] While this can be rectified by masking interrupt requests during the critical section, this requires the code in the critical section to have bounded (and preferably short) running time, or excessive interrupt latency may be observed.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure can be used to improve performance.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure increases the amount of time spent in parallel execution rather than serial execution, improving performance on a multi-core processor, because access to the shared data structure does not need to be serialized to stay coherent.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] With few exceptions, non-blocking algorithms use atomic read-modify-write primitives that the hardware must provide, the most notable of which is compare and swap (CAS).
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Critical sections are almost always implemented using standard interfaces over these primitives (in the general case, critical sections will be blocking, even when implemented with these primitives).
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In the 1990s all non-blocking algorithms had to be written "natively" with the underlying primitives to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the emerging field of software transactional memory promises standard abstractions for writing efficient non-blocking code.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Much research has also been done in providing basic data structures such as stacks, queues, sets, and hash tables.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] These allow programs to easily exchange data between threads asynchronously.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Additionally, some non-blocking data structures are weak enough to be implemented without special atomic primitives.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Several libraries internally use lock-free techniques, but it is difficult to write lock-free code that is correct.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Non-blocking algorithms generally involve a series of read, read-modify-write, and write instructions in a carefully designed order.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Optimizing compilers can aggressively re-arrange operations.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Even when they don't, many modern CPUs often re-arrange such operations (they have a "weak consistency model"), unless a memory barrier is used to tell the CPU not to reorder.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] C++11 programmers can use `std::atomic` in `<atomic>`, and C11 programmers can use `<stdatomic.h>`, both of which supply types and functions that tell the compiler not to re-arrange such instructions, and to insert the appropriate memory barriers.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-freedom is the strongest non-blocking guarantee of progress, combining guaranteed system-wide throughput with starvation-freedom.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is wait-free if every operation has a bound on the number of steps the algorithm will take before the operation completes.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] This property is critical for real-time systems and is always nice to have as long as the performance cost is not too high.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] It was shown in the 1980s that all algorithms can be implemented wait-free, and many transformations from serial code, called *universal constructions*, have been demonstrated.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the resulting performance does not in general match even naïve blocking designs.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have since improved the performance of universal constructions, but still, their performance is far below blocking designs.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have investigated the difficulty of creating wait-free algorithms.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, it has been shown that the widely available atomic *conditional* primitives, CAS and LL/SC, cannot provide starvation-free implementations of many common data structures without memory costs growing linearly in the number of threads.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] However, these lower bounds do not present a real barrier in practice, as spending a cache line or exclusive reservation granule (up to 2 KB on ARM) of store per thread in the shared memory is not considered too costly for practical systems.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Typically, the amount of store logically required is a word, but physically CAS operations on the same cache line will collide, and LL/SC operations in the same exclusive reservation granule will collide, so the amount of store physically required is greater.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-free algorithms were rare until 2011, both in research and in practice.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] However, in 2011 Kogan and Petrank presented a wait-free queue building on the CAS primitive, generally available on common hardware.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Their construction expanded the lock-free queue of Michael and Scott, which is an efficient queue often used in practice.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] A follow-up paper by Kogan and Petrank provided a method for making wait-free algorithms fast and used this method to make the wait-free queue practically as fast as its lock-free counterpart.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] A subsequent paper by Timnat and Petrank provided an automatic mechanism for generating wait-free data structures from lock-free ones.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, wait-free implementations are now available for many data-structures.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Under reasonable assumptions, Alistarh, Censor-Hillel, and Shavit showed that lock-free algorithms are practically wait-free.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, in the absence of hard deadlines, wait-free algorithms may not be worth the additional complexity that they introduce.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Lock-freedom allows individual threads to starve but guarantees system-wide throughput.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if, when the program threads are run for a sufficiently long time, at least one of the threads makes progress (for some sensible definition of progress).
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In particular, if one thread is suspended, then a lock-free algorithm guarantees that the remaining threads can still make progress.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Hence, if two threads can contend for the same mutex lock or spinlock, then the algorithm is *not* lock-free.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if infinitely often operation by some processors will succeed in a finite number of steps.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] For instance, if *N* processors are trying to execute an operation, some of the *N* processes will succeed in finishing the operation in a finite number of steps and others might fail and retry on failure.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] The difference between wait-free and lock-free is that wait-free operation by each process is guaranteed to succeed in a finite number of steps, regardless of the other processors.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In general, a lock-free algorithm can run in four phases: completing one's own operation, assisting an obstructing operation, aborting an obstructing operation, and waiting.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Completing one's own operation is complicated by the possibility of concurrent assistance and abortion, but is invariably the fastest path to completion.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] The decision about when to assist, abort or wait when an obstruction is met is the responsibility of a *contention manager*.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] This may be very simple (assist higher priority operations, abort lower priority ones), or may be more optimized to achieve better throughput, or lower the latency of prioritized operations.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Correct concurrent assistance is typically the most complex part of a lock-free algorithm, and often very costly to execute: not only does the assisting thread slow down, but thanks to the mechanics of shared memory, the thread being assisted will be slowed, too, if it is still running.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom is the weakest natural non-blocking progress guarantee.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is obstruction-free if at any point, a single thread executed in isolation (i.e., with all obstructing threads suspended) for a bounded number of steps will complete its operation.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] All lock-free algorithms are obstruction-free.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom demands only that any partially completed operation can be aborted and the changes made rolled back.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Dropping concurrent assistance can often result in much simpler algorithms that are easier to validate.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Preventing the system from continually live-locking is the task of a contention manager.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Some obstruction-free algorithms use a pair of "consistency markers" in the data structure.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Processes reading the data structure first read one consistency marker, then read the relevant data into an internal buffer, then read the other marker, and then compare the markers.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] The data is consistent if the two markers are identical.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] Markers may be non-identical when the read is interrupted by another process updating the data structure.
[src:uvloop/non-blocking-algorithm] In such a case, the process discards the data in the internal buffer and tries again.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:uvloop/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:uvloop/user-index] This section of the documentation provides information about how to use uvloop.
[src:uvloop/uvloop-readthedocs-io] You can read more about uvloop in this blog post.
[src:uvloop/uvloop-readthedocs-io] The asyncio module, introduced by PEP 3156, is a collection of network transports, protocols, and streams abstractions, with a pluggable event loop.
[src:uvloop/uvloop-readthedocs-io] libuv is a high performance, multiplatform asynchronous I/O library used by nodejs.
[src:uvloop/uvloop-readthedocs-io] Because of how wide-spread and popular nodejs is, libuv is fast and stable.
